fields.Title: WHIRLING F2 ORB / Communist Quest Initiation
fields.Condition: Variable["whirling.upd_chose_communist"] == true  and  Variable["whirling.upd_cancelled"] == false  and  Variable["whirling.orb_communist_clicked"] == false
fields.Description: Rhetoric tells you it's time to bone up on dialectical materialism and get organized.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Good luck explaining that to the Tr..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Good luck explaining that to the Tribunal of Revolutionary Retribution.

fields.Title: You: "Not really my thing. [Discard thoug..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Not really my thing. [Discard thought.]

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "The condition of your paperwork is..."
fields.Dialogue Text: The condition of your paperwork is irrelevant. All that matters is your commitment to *building the World Republic*.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Your level of personal upkeep is ir..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Your level of personal upkeep is irrelevant. All that matters is your commitment to *building the World Republic*.

fields.Title: Inland Empire: "They live underground? These commun..."
fields.Dialogue Text: They live underground? These communists aren't men, they're *mole people*!

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "It's a smell you know all too well...."
fields.Dialogue Text: It's a smell you know all too well. Simultaneously repulsive and yet darkly appealing. Musty with a sharp tang, but also a remnant of lost sweetness. Like a rotting mango that's been swaddled in a coat from your grandfather's attic...

fields.Title: Authority: "You should begin by interrogating t..."
fields.Dialogue Text: You should begin by interrogating those lawless malcontents at the Dockworkers' Union. They're an obvious place to start.

fields.Title: You: "I don't know if I want to go search..."
fields.Dialogue Text: I don't know if I want to go searching for mole people.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Failure."
fields.Dialogue Text: Failure.

fields.Title: You: "On second thought, I have better th..."
fields.Dialogue Text: On second thought, I have better things to do. [Refuse task.]

fields.Title: You: "Isn't that last part kind of counte..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Isn't that last part kind of counter-productive?

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Rise and shine, comrade. It's time..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Rise and shine, comrade. It's time to get to work.

fields.Title: You: "I'm ready, let's get to it."
fields.Dialogue Text: I'm ready, let's get to it.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Possibly? If you have been, it's on..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Possibly? If you have been, it's only because you're a *double-agent*, acting in furtherance of your *long-term objectives*.

fields.Title: Encyclopedia: "Incidentally, during the waning day..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Incidentally, during the waning days of the Antecentennial Revolution, a number of Revacholian communards constructed elaborate hideouts in abandoned root cellars, hollowed-out tree trunks, and even residential sewage tanks. This latter phenomenon gave rise to the early anti-communist slogan, 'The Future's Bright When You Flush Out the White!'

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "You must seek out your revolutionar..."
fields.Dialogue Text: You must seek out your revolutionary brothers and sisters. Find out how much communism they've built. Then, together, maybe you'll be able to build as much as 0.0002% of communism.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "They're not 'mole people', they're..."
fields.Dialogue Text: They're not 'mole people', they're your comrades in the *eternal class struggle*. It's your task to find and join them.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "First, you'll have to locate the re..."
fields.Dialogue Text: First, you'll have to locate the remaining communists in Martinaise. When you get near to someone with revolutionary potential your nose will give you the signal to *establish contact*.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "People sometimes complain there are..."
fields.Dialogue Text: People sometimes complain there are no real communists left in Martinaise, but you can smell their presence. They're out there, waiting for you to join them!

fields.Title: You: "What's going on?"
fields.Dialogue Text: What's going on?

fields.Title: You: "Judging from the state of my ledger..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Judging from the state of my ledger, I don't think that’s possible.

fields.Title: You: "But *I'm* part of the Coalition aut..."
fields.Dialogue Text: But *I'm* part of the Coalition authorities! Have I been persecuting communists this whole time?

fields.Title: You: "You must mean my *knows*, as in my..."
fields.Dialogue Text: You must mean my *knows*, as in my huge and highly functioning brain.

fields.Title: Perception (Smell): "We really have no idea what they're..."
fields.Dialogue Text: We really have no idea what they're talking about. There's no linkage between ideology and olfaction.

fields.Title: You: "Hang on, what will I do once I esta..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Hang on, what will I do once I establish contact with my fellow communists?

fields.Title: Endurance: "Uh oh. Organisation hasn't exactly..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Uh oh. Organisation hasn't exactly been your strong suit, historically speaking...

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Yes, fortunately communists are kno..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Yes, fortunately communists are known to have a very *distinct* smell.

fields.Title: You: "Hmm, probably not."
fields.Dialogue Text: Hmm, probably not.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "It's not *stupid*, it's the greates..."
fields.Dialogue Text: It's not *stupid*, it's the greatest endeavour in the history of human civilisation!

fields.Title: You: "Well, if you say so. Guess I've got..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Well, if you say so. Guess I've got to get organised, then.

fields.Title: You: "There's so much failure in my life..."
fields.Dialogue Text: There's so much failure in my life already -- I don't know if I can take any more.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "That's why you're perfect for the j..."
fields.Dialogue Text: That's why you're perfect for the job. No one's got a better nose for failure than you, detective.
fields.Alternate1: That's why you're perfect for the job. No one's got a better nose for failure than you, Harry.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "But it won't be *easy*. Decades of..."
fields.Dialogue Text: But it won't be *easy*. Decades of persecution by Coalition authorities have driven the remaining communists of Martinaise *underground*.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Just between us, you may want to la..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Just between us, you may want to lay off this 'grind up the bourgeoisie' stuff. It's a bit off-putting, even to fellow communists.

fields.Title: You: "What does communism smell like?"
fields.Dialogue Text: What does communism smell like?

fields.Title: You: "Have you *seen* my shit recently? I..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Have you *seen* my shit recently? I've really gotten it together.

fields.Title: You: "Okay, but what does *failure* smell..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Okay, but what does *failure* smell like?

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "You'll discuss the monumental, worl..."
fields.Dialogue Text: You'll discuss the monumental, world-historical task that lies before you. You'll engage in rigorous and spirited debates about Mazovian theory and practice. But mostly you'll probably complain about other communists.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Here we go! 'Wake, brave worker! 'T..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Here we go! 'Wake, brave worker! 'Tis no time for bed/ Fight till there's no slaves below, and no masters o'erhead.'

fields.Title: Jump to: [Rhetoric: "First, you'll have to locate the re..."]
You: "(Roll up your sleeves.) Alright, le..."
fields.Dialogue Text: (Roll up your sleeves.) Alright, let's get to it. [Accept task.]

fields.Title: You: "Does this mean I need to clean up m..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Does this mean I need to clean up my hostel room?
fields.Alternate1: I thought the shack was nice and cozy as-is.

fields.Title: Logic: "Judging from the bust of Kras Mazov..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Judging from the bust of Kras Mazov and other revolutionary paraphernalia you discovered, it seems that the Capeside Apartments may be a hotbed of communist activity.

fields.Title: You: "Will they help me fire up Mazov's S..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Will they help me fire up Mazov's Socialist Sausage Grinder?

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Let your *nose* guide you, detectiv..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Let your *nose* guide you, detective.

fields.Title: Perception (Smell): "Again, no, it won't. Any olfactory..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Again, no, it won't. Any olfactory response you perceive will be strictly psychosomatic.

fields.Title: Endurance: "Have you engaged the shit compresso..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Have you engaged the shit compressor? This task won't permit any looseness on your part, mentally or physically...

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "No, we meant your nose, as in that..."
fields.Dialogue Text: No, we meant your nose, as in that swollen muck-detector in the centre of your face. It just happens to be *perfectly* calibrated for sensing communists.

fields.Title: You: "This sounds unfathomably stupid. I..."
fields.Dialogue Text: This sounds unfathomably stupid. I want no part of it.

fields.Title: You: "No, going around sniffing communist..."
fields.Dialogue Text: No, going around sniffing communists is definitely stupid. Forget about it. [Refuse task.]

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "It's good that your *personal* busi..."
fields.Dialogue Text: It's good that your *personal* business is in order, but we're talking about political matters of world-historical import here.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Regardless, what's past is past. Yo..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Regardless, what's past is past. You need to look forward, to the work of building communism for all.

fields.Title: Logic: "Listen to this. Do you really think..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Listen to this. Do you really think you're the kind of person an underground communist cell would entrust with a mission that requires such discretion?

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Despite all the thinking you've bee..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Despite all the thinking you've been doing, only 0.0001% of communism has been built. It's too great a task to undertake alone. You're going to have to *get organised*.

fields.Title: You: "How am I supposed to find them if t..."
fields.Dialogue Text: How am I supposed to find them if they're hiding? (Proceed.)

fields.Title: You: "My *nose*?"
fields.Dialogue Text: My *nose*?

fields.Title: Logic: "You could also just look for more t..."
fields.Dialogue Text: You could also just look for more tangible evidence of communist activity. Images of Kras Mazov and white antlers are usually a dead giveaway.

fields.Title: Jump to: [Rhetoric: "Good luck explaining that to the Tr..."]
Rhetoric: "That's the spirit, comrade!"
fields.Dialogue Text: That's the spirit, comrade!

fields.Title: Perception (Smell): "What you're smelling is your own bo..."
fields.Dialogue Text: What you're smelling is your own body odour, of course. Nothing a shower and change of clothes couldn't fix.

fields.Title: You: "Okay, I'm ready. Let's get organise..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Okay, I'm ready. Let's get organised.

fields.Title: Rhetoric: "Not at all. Complaining about other..."
fields.Dialogue Text: Not at all. Complaining about other communists is one of the most important parts of being a communist.

fields.Title: You: "Maybe?"
fields.Dialogue Text: Maybe?
